04307nam a22006015i 9780773554030DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735540307 a10.1515/97807735540302doi  a(DE-B1597)657612  a(OCoLC)1035259538  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aN6544b.H86 2018 7aART0650002bisacsh04a704/.04209712231 aHuneault, Kristina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aI'm Not Myself at All :bWomen, Art, and Subjectivity in Canada /cKristina Huneault. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b145 illustrations, full colour throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v2500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tIdentities -- tAbsence -- tDisplacements -- tGaps -- tForces -- tDiversity -- tInclination -- tListening -- tCoda -- tIllustrations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNotions of identity have long structured women’s art. Dynamics of race, class, and gender have shaped the production of artworks and oriented their subsequent reassessments. Arguably, this is especially true of art by women, and of the socially engaged criticism that addresses it. If identity has been a problem in women’s art, however, is more identity the solution? In this study of nineteenth- and early twentieth-century art in Canada, Kristina Huneault offers a meditation on the strictures of identity and an exploration of forces that unsettle and realign the self. Looking closely at individual artists and works, Huneault combines formal analysis with archival research and philosophical inquiry, building nuanced readings of objects that range from the canonical to the largely unknown. Whether in miniature portraits or genre paintings, botanical drawings or baskets, women artists reckoned with constraints that limited understandings of themselves and others. They also forged creative alternatives. At times identity features in women’s artistic work as a failed project; at other times it marks a boundary beyond which they were able to expand, explore, and exult. Bringing together settler and indigenous forms of cultural expression and foregrounding the importance of colonialism within the development of art in Canada, I’m Not Myself at All observes and reactivates historical art by women and prompts readers to consider what a less restrictive conceptualization of selfhood might bring to current patterns of cultural analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtzCanadaxHistory. 0aArt, Canadiany19th century. 0aArt, Canadiany20th century. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in art. 0aIndigenous womenzCanada. 0aWomen artistszCanada. 0aWomen in art. 7aART / Women Artists.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355403040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773554030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773554030/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles